# User Manual Maintenance Rule

`doc/user-manual.qmd` is the living end-user guide for X2Chess. It must
accurately reflect the current state of the application at all times.

## When to update

Update the user manual **in the same session** as any change that falls into
one of these categories:

| Category | Examples |
|---|---|
| New user-facing feature | New dialog, new toolbar button, new panel, new mode |
| Changed behavior | Button renamed, workflow altered, keyboard shortcut changed |
| Removed feature | Panel removed, button disabled/hidden, mode dropped |
| New keyboard shortcut | Any new or changed shortcut |
| New configuration option | New menu item, new setting, new schema field type |
| Changed terminology | Label rename visible to the user |

Do **not** update the manual for: pure refactoring, CSS changes, internal
module splits, type changes, test additions, or performance improvements that
have no visible effect.

## Required changes when updating

1. **Update "Last updated" date** at the top to today's date (`YYYY-MM-DD`).
2. **Add, edit, or remove** the relevant section(s) — never leave a section
   that contradicts current behavior.
3. **Write for end users**, not implementers. Concrete action/result phrasing:
   *"Click X to do Y"* not *"The handler dispatches action Z"*.
4. **Do not document planned features** as if they are implemented. If a
   feature is in-plan but not yet in the UI, omit it.

## Section checklist

When finishing a session with user-facing changes, run through these sections
and update any that are affected:

- [ ] Application layout overview
- [ ] Opening and managing games (drag/drop, paste, new game dialog)
- [ ] Game info and metadata
- [ ] Navigation (toolbar buttons, keyboard shortcuts)
- [ ] PGN text editor (layout modes, comments, Q/A, directives)
- [ ] Chess board (move entry, disambiguation, promotion, flip, hint, extract)
- [ ] Saving (save button, autosave/manual mode, undo/redo)
- [ ] Engine analysis (start/stop, variations, vs engine, annotate)
- [ ] Opening explorer (toggle, source, settings)
- [ ] Tablebase (toggle, results)
- [ ] Study mode (requirements, workflow)
- [ ] Training mode (launcher, protocols, result/merge)
- [ ] Resource viewer (browse, group-by, filter, schema editor, new game)
- [ ] Menu panel (all menu items)
- [ ] Developer tools (dock tabs, diagnostic panels)
- [ ] Keyboard shortcuts summary table

## Documentation discipline

- Step-by-step numbered lists for multi-step workflows.
- Tables for reference material (shortcuts, options).
- Avoid internal jargon (`dispatch`, `reducer`, `hook`, `selector`, etc.).
- Keep each section self-contained — a user should not need to read the whole
  manual to understand one workflow.
- If behavior differs between platforms (macOS vs Windows), note both.
